    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9b92416d-c66a-4662-a72b-e86f881b5187",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 34-year-old woman with a warm, energetic presence, though today she appears visibly uncomfortable — shifting in her seat, wincing occasionally, and holding her lower abdomen. She is of average build (height 165 cm, weight 62 kg), with dark brown hair pulled back in a ponytail and tired eyes that suggest she has not been sleeping well over the past few days. She works as a primary school teacher, a job she is deeply passionate about, and spends her weekdays on her feet in a busy classroom environment. She lives with her husband and their two young children (ages 3 and 6) in a suburban home and describes her lifestyle as \"organized chaos.\" She enjoys weekend hiking, yoga on Tuesday evenings, and cooking Mediterranean-inspired meals. She is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol only socially, roughly 1–2 glasses of wine per week. She drinks approximately 1.5 liters of water daily, though she admits this drops significantly on busy school days when she sometimes skips bathroom breaks for hours at a time.\n\n{patientName} reports a 3-day history of a burning, stinging sensation during urination (dysuria), a frequent and urgent need to urinate — sometimes every 15–20 minutes — and a sense of incomplete bladder emptying. She describes her urine as cloudy and notably darker than usual, with an unpleasant odor. She denies any fever, chills, nausea, vomiting, or flank pain, which makes an upper urinary tract infection (pyelonephritis) less likely at this stage. She rates her discomfort at 6/10 and says the symptoms are interfering with her ability to teach and care for her children. She has not started any treatment yet and came in today seeking relief.\n\n{patientName} is generally health-conscious and keeps up with her annual check-ups. She is not currently pregnant and uses a copper intrauterine device (IUD) for contraception, which she has had in place for two years without complications. She reports no vaginal discharge or odor, and her last gynecological exam was six months ago with no abnormal findings. She mentions that she has had two similar episodes in the past — one approximately 18 months ago and another about 3 years ago — both of which were treated successfully with a short course of oral antibiotics.\n\n{patientName} appears mildly distressed due to urinary discomfort but is otherwise alert, oriented, and cooperative. Her vital signs are within normal limits. She is well-dressed and articulate, asking specific questions about whether her IUD could be contributing to her infections and whether there are lifestyle changes she can make to prevent recurrence. She is motivated and receptive to education, making her an excellent candidate for counseling on preventive strategies such as adequate hydration, post-coital voiding, and hygiene practices."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5a434efe-69aa-4adf-8fb1-90e5274ff198",
      "resource": {
