        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a relatively unremarkable past medical history. She experienced two prior episodes of urinary tract infection — one approximately 18 months ago and another 3 years ago — both treated successfully with oral antibiotics (trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole on the first occasion, nitrofurantoin on the second). There were no complications or hospitalizations associated with either episode, and urine cultures were not recalled by the patient. She has no history of urological abnormalities, kidney stones, or recurrent UTIs meeting formal criteria for recurrence (≥3 episodes/year).\n\n{patientName} has no chronic medical conditions such as diabetes mellitus, hypertension, or immunodeficiency. Her surgical history includes two uncomplicated vaginal deliveries. She has no known drug allergies. Her current medications are limited to a daily multivitamin and occasional ibuprofen for tension headaches. She uses a copper IUD (Paragard) as her primary contraceptive method, in place for 2 years without complications.\n\nFamily history is notable for type 2 diabetes mellitus in her mother and hypertension in her father. There is no known family history of urological malignancy or renal disease. {patientName} is a non-smoker, consumes alcohol in moderation, and exercises regularly. She does not use recreational drugs. She reports moderate occupational stress related to teaching but denies symptoms of anxiety or depression and is not on any psychotropic medications."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
